  1. What is the EPSG code of the Counties dataset? Is this a geographic or a projected coordinate reference system? (Om other words, does this CRS use angular or planar coordinate units?) To what datum is this CRS associated? (Tip: look for the EPSG code on https://epsg.io)

ANSWER: The EPSG code for the Counties dataset is EPSG:4269, which corresponds to the NAD83 (North American Datum 1983) geographic coordinate reference system. This CRS uses angular units (degrees of latitude and longitude) rather than planar units, making it a geographic rather than a projected CRS. The datum, NAD83, is commonly used for datasets in North America and is based on the GRS 1980 ellipsoid. This means the datasets coordinates are represented on a curved surface rather than a flat plane.

  1. What columns in the dataset contain the x and y coordinate values, respectively?
    > ANSWER: > In the nwis_data dataset, the columns containing the coordinate values are dec_long_va and dec_lat_va, which represent longitude (x-coordinate) and latitude (y-coordinate), respectively. These columns provide the geographic location of each site, with dec_lat_va for the north-south positioning (latitude) and dec_long_va for the east-west positioning (longitude). This coordinate information allows spatial mapping and analysis of the gage locations across Nebraska.

Convert the dataframe to a spatial features (sf) dataframe

  1. Convert the dataframe to an sf dataframe. * Note: These data use the same coordinate reference system as the counties dataset
# Convert to an sf dataframe using longitude and latitude columns, and set CRS to EPSG:4269
nwis_sf <- st_as_sf(nwis_data, 
                    coords = c("dec_long_va", "dec_lat_va"), 
                    crs = 4269)  # Set the CRS to EPSG:4269 (NAD83)

  1. What new field(s) appear in the sf dataframe created? What field(s), if any, disappeared?

ANSWER: After converting the nwis_data dataframe to an sf dataframe, the new field that appears is geometry, which stores the spatial coordinates as point geometries (sfc_POINT). This field combines the latitude and longitude data into a single spatial object. As a result, the original coordinate columns, dec_lat_va and dec_long_va, disappear from the dataframe since their information is now encapsulated in the geometry column. This conversion enables the dataframe to be used for spatial operations and analyses.

Read in the gage height data and join the site location data to it.

Lastly, we want to attach some gage height data to our site locations. Ive constructed a csv file listing many of the Nebraska gage sites, by station name and site number along with stream gage heights (in meters) recorded during the recent flood event. This file is titled NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv and is found in the Data/Raw folder.

  1. Read the NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv dataset in as a dataframe
    • Pay attention to which fields should be imported as factors!
# Read in the NWIS Site Flow Data CSV file
nwis_raw <- read.csv("Data/Raw/NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv", 
                        colClasses = (c("site_no"="factor")),
                                     stringsAsFactors = TRUE)
  1. Show the column names.
# Show the column names of the dataset
colnames(nwis_raw)
## [1] "site_no"    "station_nm" "date"       "gage_ht"
  1. Join our site information (already imported above) to these gage height data
    • The site_no and station_nm can both/either serve as joining attributes
    • Construct this join so that the result only includes records features where both tables have data (N=136)
sdf_gages_joined <- nwis_sf %>%
  inner_join(nwis_raw, by = "site_no")

# Perform the join using merge() and specifying the 'site_no' as the key for both datasets
gage_data_with_sites <- merge(
  x = nwis_sf,  # This is the raw gage height data
  y = nwis_raw,   # This is the site information spatial data
  by.x = "station_nm",  # The 'station_nm' column in the gage height data
  by.y = "station_nm",  # The 'station_nm' column in the site information data
  all = FALSE  # Ensures the join is an inner join (only matching records are kept)
)

# Check if the join resulted in 136 records
nrow(gage_data_with_sites)  # Should return 136
## [1] 136
  1. Show the column names of this resulting spatial dataframe
# Show the column names of the resulting spatial dataframe
colnames(gage_data_with_sites)
## [1] "station_nm"         "site_no.x"          "site_tp_cd"        
## [4] "coord_acy_cd"       "dec_coord_datum_cd" "site_no.y"         
## [7] "date"               "gage_ht"            "geometry"
  1. Show the dimensions of the resulting joined dataframe
# Show the dimensions (number of rows and columns) of the resulting joined dataframe

SPATIAL ANALYSIS

Up next we will do some spatial analysis with our data. To prepare for this, we should transform our data into a projected coordinate system. Well choose UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).

Transform the counties and gage site datasets to UTM Zone 14N

  1. Transform the counties and gage sf datasets to UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).
# Transform counties to UTM Zone 14N (EPSG: 32614)
counties_sf_utm <- st_transform(nebraska_counties, crs = 32614)

# Transform gage sites to UTM Zone 14N (EPSG: 32614)
gage_data_utm <- st_transform(gage_data_with_sites, crs = 32614)
  1. Using mapview or ggplot, plot the data so that each can be seen as different colors
# Create interactive map with different colors for each layer
mapview(counties_sf_utm, col.regions = "blue") +
  mapview(gage_data_utm, col.regions = "red")

Select the gages falling within a given county

Now lets zoom into a particular county and examine the gages located there. 22. Select Lancaster county from your projected county sf dataframe

# Filter the county sf dataframe for Lancaster County
lancaster_county <- counties_sf_utm %>% 
  filter(NAME == "Lancaster")
  1. Select the gage sites falling within that county to a new spatial dataframe
# Use st_intersection to find gage sites within Lancaster County
lancaster_gages <- st_intersection(gage_data_utm, lancaster_county)
  1. Select the gage sites within 15km of the county to a new spatial dataframe
# Create a 15 km buffer around Lancaster County
lancaster_buffer <- st_buffer(lancaster_county, dist = 15000)

# Select gage sites that intersect with the buffer
lancaster_gages_within_15km <- st_intersection(gage_data_utm, lancaster_buffer)
  1. Create a plot showing (each symbolized distinctly):
  • all Nebraska counties,
  • the selected county,
  • the gage sites in that county,
  • and the gage sites within 15 km of the county
# Plot the map
ggplot() +
  # Plot all counties in Nebraska with a light gray color
  geom_sf(data = counties_sf_utm, fill = "lightgray", color = "black") +
  
  # Highlight Lancaster County in a distinct color, such as blue
  geom_sf(data = lancaster_county, fill = "blue", color = "black", alpha = 0.5) +
  
  # Plot gage sites within Lancaster County with a different symbol, such as filled circles
  geom_sf(data = lancaster_gages, color = "red", shape = 16, size = 2, 
          show.legend = TRUE) +
  
  # Plot gage sites within 15 km of Lancaster County with another symbol, such as hollow circles
  geom_sf(data = lancaster_gages_within_15km, color = "purple", shape = 1, size = 2, 
          show.legend = TRUE) +
  
  # Add a title and labels
  labs(title = "Gage Sites in and near Lancaster County, Nebraska",
       subtitle = "Red: Within Lancaster County, Purple: Within 15 km of Lancaster County") +
  
  # Set coordinate system
  coord_sf() +
  
  # Optional theme for clarity
  theme_minimal()
